{"title_page": "Saltoro Kangri", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Saltoro Kangri\n| photo = Saltoro Kangri.jpg\n| photo_caption = Saltoro Kangri, at right\n| elevation_m = 7742\n| elevation_ref = <small>[[List of highest mountains|Ranked 31st]]</small>\n| prominence_m = 2160\n| prominence_ref = \n| range = [[Saltoro Mountains]], [[Karakoram]]\n| listing = [[Ultra prominent peak|Ultra]]\n| location = [[Actual Ground Position Line]], [[Saltoro Mountains]] on the border between India and Pakistan controlled territories\n| map = Pakistan\n| map_caption = Gilgat baltistan\n| map_size = 300\n| label_position = right\n| coordinates = {{coord|35|23|57.6|N|76|50|55.2|E|type:mountain_dim:{{Infobox dim|length_km=80}}|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = \n| length_km = 80\n| range_coordinates = \n| first_ascent = 24 July 1962 by Y. Takamura, A. Saito, Capt. Bashir<ref name=AJ_1964/>\n| easiest_route = rock/snow/ice climb\n}}\n\n'''Saltoro Kangri''' is the highest peak of the [[Saltoro Mountains]], also known as the '''Saltoro Range''', which is a part of the [[Karakoram]]. It is the 31st [[List of highest mountains|highest mountain]] in the world, but it is in a very remote location deep in the Karakoram.  It is located on the [[Actual Ground Position Line]] between Indian controlled territory in the Siachen region and Pakistani controlled territory in the Saltoro Range.\n__NOTOC__\n\n== Climbing history ==\nThe mountain was reconnoitered by the intrepid Workman couple in 1911-12. The first attempt on the peak was in 1935 by a British expedition led by J. Waller, which reached c.24500' on the SE ridge.<ref name=HJ_1936/><ref name=HJ_1937/> A British university expedition led by [[Eric Shipton]] approached this peak through the [[Bilafond La]] via Pakistan with a Pakistani climbing permit. They reached the peak but did not attempt it. This expedition was inadvertently the first move in the deadly game of Siachen [[oropolitics]] that would lead to the [[Siachen conflict]] of 1984.<ref name=HJ_1958/>\n\nThe first ascent of Saltoro Kangri was in July 1962, by a joint Japanese-Pakistani expedition led by T. Shidei. This piggyback expedition put A. Saito, Y. Takamura and Pakistani climber R.A. Bashir on top on July 24, following the S.E. ridge route.<ref name=AJ_1964/><ref name=HJ_1964/> This peak was climbed by an Indian Army expedition led by [[Colonel (India)|Colonel]] [[Narendra Kumar (mountaineer)|Narendra Kumar]] in 1981.<ref name=Kapadia2005/> US maps of the area and many world atlases starting in the 1960s showed the [[Line of Control]] between Pakistani and Indian territory running from the last defined point in the 1949 [[Karachi Agreement]], [[NJ9842]], east-northeast to the [[Karakoram Pass]], thus putting the whole of Saltoro Kangri and the entire [[Siachen Glacier]] in Pakistan.  However, the [[Simla Agreement]] defined the Line of Control no further than point NJ9842 other than with the phrase \"thence north to the glaciers.\" The [http://www.alpine-club.org.uk/hi/ Himalayan Index] lists only one more ascent of the mountain, in 1981, and no other attempts.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sia Kangri]]\n*[[Indira Col]]\n*[[List of mountains in India]]\n*[[List of mountains in Pakistan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=AJ_1964>\n  {{cite journal | title = The Ascent of Saltoro Kangri | author = Shidei, T.\n  | journal = [[Alpine Journal]] | year = 1964 | volume = 69 | pages = 73-80\n  | url = https://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1964_files/AJ%201964%2073-80%20Shidei%20Saltoro%20Kangri.pdf\n  | url-status = live | access-date = 2020-01-15}}</ref>\n<ref name=HJ_1936>\n  {{cite journal | title = Peak 36, Saltoro Karakoram, 1935 | author = Hunt, John\n  | journal = [[Himalayan Journal]] | year = 1936 | volume = 8 | pages = \n  | url = https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/08/2/peak-36-saltoro-karakoram-1935/\n  | url-status = live | access-date = 2020-01-15}}</ref>\n<ref name=HJ_1937>\n  {{cite journal | title = Peak 36, Saltoro Karakoram A Mountaineering Analysis\n  | author1 = Hunt, John | author2 = Waller, James\n  | journal = [[Himalayan Journal]] | year = 1937 | volume = 9 | pages = \n  | url = https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/09/13/peak-36-saltoro-karakoram-a-mountaineering-analysis/\n  | url-status = live | access-date = 2020-01-15}}</ref>\n<ref name=HJ_1958>\n  {{cite journal | title = The Imperial College Karakoram Expedition, 1957\n  | author = Miller, K.J.\n  | journal = [[Himalayan Journal]] | year = 1958 | volume = 21 | pages = \n  | url = https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/21/3/the-imperial-college-karakoram-expedition-1957/\n  | url-status = live | access-date = 2020-01-15}}</ref>\n<ref name=HJ_1964>\n  {{cite journal | title = The Ascent of Saltoro Kangri | author = Shidei, T.\n  | journal = [[Himalayan Journal]] | year = 1964 | volume = 25 | pages = \n  | url = https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/25/17/pakistan-japan-joint-kara-koram-expedition-to-saltoro-kangri-1962/\n  | url-status = live | access-date = 2020-01-15}}</ref>\n<ref name=Kapadia2005>\n  {{cite book | title = Into the Untravelled Himalaya: Travels, Treks, and Climbs\n  | author = Kapadia, Harish | year = 2005 | publisher = Indus Publishing | page = 245\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=-5l1RhMStxgC&pg=PA245\n  | url-status = live | access-date = 2020-01-15}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* Jill Neate, ''High Asia: An Illustrated History of the 7000 Metre Peaks'', {{ISBN|0-89886-238-8}}\n* [http://www.alpine-club.org.uk/hi/ Himalayan Index]\n* [http://www.viewfinderpanoramas.org/dem3.html#himalayas DEM files for the Himalaya] (Corrected versions of SRTM data)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=10533 \"Saltoro Kangri, India/Pakistan\" on Peakbagger]\n* [http://peaklist.org/WWlists/ultras/karakoram.html \"The Karakoram, Pakistan Himalaya and India Himalaya (north of Nepal) on Peaklist]\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Seven-thousanders of the Karakoram]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Saltoro Kangri\n| photo = Saltoro Kangri.jpg\n| photo_caption = Saltoro Kangri, at right\n| elevation_m = 7742\n| elevation_ref = <small>[[List of highest mountains|Ranked 31st]]</small>\n| prominence_m = 2160\n| prominence_ref = \n| range = [[Saltoro Mountains]], [[Karakoram]]\n| listing = [[Ultra prominent peak|Ultra]]\n| location = [[Actual Ground Position Line]], [[Saltoro Mountains]] on the border between Indian and Pakistani controlled territories\n| map = Tibetan Plateau#India Ladakh\n| map_caption = Tibetan Plateau\n| map_size = 300\n| label_position = right\n| coordinates = {{coord|35|23|57.6|N|76|50|55.2|E|type:mountain_dim:{{Infobox dim|length_km=80}}|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = \n| length_km = 80\n| range_coordinates = \n| first_ascent = 24 July 1962 by Y. Takamura, A. Saito, Capt. Bashir<ref name=AJ_1964/>\n| easiest_route = rock/snow/ice climb\n}}\n\n'''Saltoro Kangri''' is the highest peak of the [[Saltoro Mountains]], also known as the '''Saltoro Range''', which is a part of the [[Karakoram]]. It is the 31st [[List of highest mountains|highest mountain]] in the world, but it is in a very remote location deep in the Karakoram.  It is located on the [[Actual Ground Position Line]] between Indian controlled territory in the Siachen region and Pakistani controlled territory west of the Saltoro Range.\n__NOTOC__\n== Climbing history ==\nThe mountain was reconnoitered by the intrepid Workman couple in 1911-12. The first attempt on the peak was in 1935 by a British expedition led by J. Waller, which reached c.24500' on the SE ridge.<ref name=HJ_1936/><ref name=HJ_1937/> A British university expedition led by [[Eric Shipton]] approached this peak through the [[Bilafond La]] via Pakistan with a Pakistani climbing permit. They reached the peak but did not attempt it. This expedition was inadvertently the first move in the deadly game of Siachen [[oropolitics]] that would lead to the [[Siachen conflict]] of 1984.<ref name=HJ_1958/>\n\nThe first ascent of Saltoro Kangri was in July 1962, by a joint Japanese-Pakistani expedition led by T. Shidei. This piggyback expedition put A. Saito, Y. Takamura and Pakistani climber R.A. Bashir on top on July 24, following the S.E. ridge route.<ref name=AJ_1964/><ref name=HJ_1964/> This peak was climbed by an Indian Army expedition led by [[Colonel (India)|Colonel]] [[Narendra Kumar (mountaineer)|Narendra Kumar]] in 1981.<ref name=Kapadia2005/> US maps of the area and many world atlases starting in the 1960s showed the [[Line of Control]] between Pakistani and Indian territory running from the last defined point in the 1949 [[Karachi Agreement]], [[NJ9842]], east-northeast to the [[Karakoram Pass]], thus putting the whole of Saltoro Kangri and the entire [[Siachen Glacier]] in Pakistan.  However, the [[Simla Agreement]] defined the Line of Control no further than point NJ9842 other than with the phrase \"thence north to the glaciers.\" The [http://www.alpine-club.org.uk/hi/ Himalayan Index] lists only one more ascent of the mountain, in 1981, and no other attempts.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sia Kangri]]\n*[[Indira Col]]\n*[[List of mountains in India]]\n*[[List of mountains in Pakistan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=AJ_1964>\n  {{cite journal | title = The Ascent of Saltoro Kangri | author = Shidei, T.\n  | journal = [[Alpine Journal]] | year = 1964 | volume = 69 | pages = 73-80\n  | url = https://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1964_files/AJ%201964%2073-80%20Shidei%20Saltoro%20Kangri.pdf\n  | url-status = live | access-date = 2020-01-15}}</ref>\n<ref name=HJ_1936>\n  {{cite journal | title = Peak 36, Saltoro Karakoram, 1935 | author = Hunt, John\n  | journal = [[Himalayan Journal]] | year = 1936 | volume = 8 | pages = \n  | url = https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/08/2/peak-36-saltoro-karakoram-1935/\n  | url-status = live | access-date = 2020-01-15}}</ref